{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060057A/1930101701/0129.xml":{"full_text":"A-2\nBYRD IS CRITICAL\nOF DROUGHT RELIEF\nU. S. Measures Inadequate\nfor Virginia, He Tells\nFederal Official.\n\u00a37 the Associated Press.\nRICHMOND, Va.. October 17\u2014The\nopinion that aid so far announced by\nthe Federal Government is not in any\nway adequate to meet the conditions\nproduced by the drought in Virginia\nwas expressed today by Harry F. Byrd,\nchairman of Virginia\u2019s Drought Relief\nCommittee in a lengthy communication\nto C. W. Warburton, secretary of the\nFederal Committee.\nThe letter is in reply to a telegram\nfrom the Federal secretary setting forth\nthe drought relief measures offered by\nthe Federal Government. Byrd today\ncriticised these measures as so bound\nup with restrictions as to make them\nfar from adequate, especially to aid\nthose moat In need of assistance.\nMr. Byrd said: \u201cIf I am correct in\naiy interpretation of what has been\ndone, the Federal Government, as such,\nhas done one thing only to aid in the\nemergency, and that is to permit the\nanticipation of the 1931 road fund as\naoon as the projects can be approved.\nValue la Doubted.\n\u201cEven this will be of very doubtful\nvalue, because, as previously stated, this\nfund must be expended on costly roads\nunder drastic restrictions, and will, only\ncontribute to a small degree to the re\nlief of unemployment. On the authority\nof the Oovemor of Virginia, however, I\ncan state that Virginia will avail her\nself to the limit of this fund, although\nI anticipate disappointment as to its\nbeneficial results.\u201d\nChairman Byrd requests the secretary\nof the Federal Committee to make\nknown before the meeting of the State\nCommittee October 29 whether any ad\nditional measures are contemplated by\nthe Federal Government. Ha suggested\nat the same time three measures, as\nfollow*:\n(1) That Congress authorize a gen\nerous road appropriation to be matched\nby the Btates, to be expended on cheaper\ntypes of construction. #0 that employ\nment might be given throughout the\nBUte Instead of on a few costly proj\n(2l The extension of reasonable\ncredit to worthy farmers, secured by\ncrop liens to be paid back. next year,\nwithout unnecSsary restrictions.\nPurchase sf Seeds.\n(3) Purchase by the Federal Gov\nernment of large quantities of fertiliser,\nseed and feed, which under this ar\nrangement might be obtained and fur\nnished to the farmers at great reduc\ntion in cost.\nCriticising In order the Federal\ndrought relief measures which Mr.\nWarburton had oalled to his attention,\nthe Virginia chairman said the reduc\ntion in freight rates by the railroads\nhad been beneficial, but that the bene\nfits did not reach the farmer unable\nto pay cash for the feed.\nThe $200,000 allotted to Virginia for\nFederal seed loans for planting Fall\npasture crops, Byrd said, was so bound\nup with restrictions that only $43,000\nhad been used. Pointing out that the\ntime limit for these loans had expired\nand that the continued drought made\nFall planting of pastures useless except\nin limited areas, Byrd criticised the re\nstrictions.\nJ/VORK WILL START\nSOON ON NEW CARRIER\nFOR NAVAL AIRCRAFT\nt (Continued From First Page.l\npriations totaling $4,050,000 have been\nmade by Congress for starting con\nstruction.\nBids for the carrier were opened\nSeptember 3, three companies seeking\nto do the job.\nThe Navy\u2019s two giant aircraft car\nriers, U. 8. 8. Lexington and Saratoga,\n-were originally designed as cruisers,\ntout under the Washington Arms treaty.\nshey were redesigned as aircraft car\ngiers. The experimental aircraft car\nrier. U. 8. 8. Langley, was formerly a\ncollier.\nLoss Here of $6$\u00ab,MO\nConstruction of some of the turret\nstructure for the new cruiser, to be built\ntot the Mare Island. Calif., Navy Yard,\nhitherto done at the Washington Navy\nYard for vessels of this type, will be\naccomplished by the shipbuilder on the\nWest Coast. This will involve the loss\nof nearly $BOO,OOO that would ordinarily\ngo to the local yard, The Star learned\ntoday.\nAll guns and ordnance equipment,\ntinder cognizance of the Bureau of Ord\nnance. Navy Department, for the new\nEiaer and for the new aircraft car\nto be built at Newport Newa, Va.,\nwill be built at the local yard, officials\n\u2022aid, but will not alter the employment\nsituation here materially. The Bureau\nof Construction and Repair of the Navy\nDepartment, of which Rear Admiral\nGeorge H. Rock is the chief, has decided\nthat instead of having the turret fea\ntures for the Mare Island cruiser con\nstructed here, they will be built at the\nCalifornia Navy Yard.\nNaval officials here made it plain\nthat the decision to hare the turret\nwork done on the West Coast does not\nreflect upon the workmanship at the\nWashington Navy Yard, but insisted\ngthat this is a readoption of a long\nblished practice in the shipbuilding\nistry- As the Washington Navy\nk had done quite a bit of work on\nturrets, before the designs werw\nAltered to conform to advance ideas\nIn shipbuilding, the officials said, it\nwas decided to permit the local yard\nto go ahead and finish the revised\nprogram.\nCustom to Parallel Work.\nThe evolution of the modern cruiser\nfrom the comparatively light vessel to\nheavier armor has had a large part in\nthe decision to ship the work from\nWashington, the officials said. It has\nbeen the custom in the case of battle\nships to have the shipbuilder construct\nthe turrets at the same time that the\nship was built, they explained, having\nthe two processes parallel.\nAs Uncle Sam's cruisers have now\nassumed armored ship features, the\nnaval authorities said they have decided\nto revert to the practive, now obtaining\nIn battleship construction, under which\nthe turrets are built by the constructor,\nnear where the vessel is being raised.\nNaval officials declined to disclose\nwhat ordnance the new aircraft carrier\nwill be equipped with, but the new\ncruiser which is to be a sister ship of\nthe New Orleans, now under construc\ntion at the New York Navy Yard, will\ntoe equipped with nine t-lnch guns, four\nS-lnch anti-aircraft guns ana two 21-\nInch triple torpedo tubes.\nOfficials of the Bureau of Ordnance\n\u2022aid that all guns and ordnance under\nthe cognizance of that bureau would\nbe constructed at the Washington Navy\nYard. Hitherto, the Washington Navy\nYard has done the turret work for the\nBureau of Construction and Repair, and\nthis has been shipped assembled to\nwhere the ship was under construction.\nLittie Effect Here.\nIn the opinion of the officials, the\nnumber of workmen at the Washington\nNavy Yard will not be affected by the\nnew construction as the cruiser and air\ncraft carrier, to any marked extent. It\nwill, however, fail to stem the tide of\ngradual reductions In the working force,\nunder which about 1,000 men were\ntaken on by Rear Admiral Arthur L.\nWillard, when commandant of the\nWashington Navy Yard, to take care\n9f the 1$ cruisers that Congress ordered\ni\nMRS. HOOVER AT ORCHID SHOW\nI\"- 1 r\nwr*\nKJp 1\nR jpMi\nm j K\nMHR JUII mam ..J w.*m\n\u25a0tip Jfl\nf' T v T\u2019t\n\nPH iMnjgtfi!,-\nMrs. Hoover attended the first showing of rare orchids when the display\nopened at the Willard Hotel yesterday. To the right of Mrs. Hoover is Mrs.\nEverett Gann. They are standing behind the largest orchid in existence.\n\u2014Wide World Photo.\nBRITISHER CHOSEN\nFOR FIRST ORATOR\nDrawing for International\nContest Held Today\u2014Seven\nOthers to Speak.\nJack Mallard German, England's\ncandidate for the world championship In\nhigh school speech making, will be the\nfirst of eight young speakers to take the\nstage in the fifth International Ora\ntorical Contest finals in Constitution\nHall Saturday night, October 25.\nThis was determined today when the\nresults of a drawing, made by Fleming\nNewbold, business manager of The Eve\nning Star, to determine the speaking\norder of the contestants, were an\nnounced by Randolph' Leigh, contest\ndirector general. In the drawing, the\nnames of the represented nations were\nprinted on slips of paper, which then\nwere turned face down. Mr. Newbold\nselected the slips one at a time and\nas the countries' names were read, their\nrespective orators were listed for the\nprogram.\nLloyd George Is Topic.\nAfter young German's oration on\n\"Lloyd George,\u201d the other contestants\nand their respective speech subjects will\nbe heard in the following order:\nClemente Peres-Zanartu of Santiago,\nChile, champion of Bouth America, on\n\u201cBolivar and Ban Martin.\u201d\nHeins Bockhacker of Wuppertal-El\nberfeld, Germany, on \"What Does-His\ntory Mean to the Young Generation.\"\nPaul Leduce br Quebec, Canada, on\n\"Canada and International Peace.\u201d\nAndre P. J. Fioux of Montferrand,\nFrance, on \"Liberty, Equality and Fra\nternity\";\nJavier Vivanco R.. of Mexico City,\nMexico, on \"Rationalism and Its New\nIdeology\";\nMarshall la Gulllon\u2019a Theme.\nEdmund A. Gullion of Washington,\nchampion of the United States, on\n\u201cJohn Marshall and Federal Suprem\nacy,\u201d and\nWilliam Hayes of Rathfarnham, Ire\nland, on \u201cIreland.\"\nYoung Gullion, the Western High\nSchool boy. who captured the United i\nStates championship In the National\nfinals here last May. was the third ora\ntor to speak in that contest. As set up\nby the drawing, the various languages\nare fairly well distributed oh the pro\ngram. English opens and closes the\nmeet and from tne standpoint of the\naudience, the contestant orations will\nbe linguistic assembly, talking. In or\nder, English. Spanish. German. French\n(for France), French (for Canada),\nSpanish. English and English.\nThe judges, who will be announced\ntomorrow, are multilinguists, capable of\nweighing the merits of all the orations\nin the languages used.\nTOWN CAPTURED,\nCOUNCIL ROUTED\nArmed Mexioan Band Takes Reins\nof Government at\nComitan.\nBy the Associated Press.\nMEXICO CITY, October 17.\u2014A dis\npatch to Excelsior from Comitan, state\nof Chiapas, today said that a body of\narmed men, headed by Leocadlo Velasco,\nhad taken posseaelon of that town, oust\ning municipal authorities and calling\nleading citiaens to a conference to\nchoose a new municipal council.\nThe correspondent said the movement\napparently was against the state au\nthorities. federal officers in Comitan\nbeing unmolested. The custom office\ncontinued to function and commercial\nestablishments remained open. The\ncity wss described today as tranquil.\nComitan is the most important de\npartment in the State of Chiapas, and\nhas about 60,000 inhabitants, of whom\none-sixth live in the city of Comitan,\nwhich is several miles from the Guate\nmalan frontier.\nSues for Personal Injuries.\nAnthony Barbra, trading as Universal\nElectric Co., 624 E street, was sued for\nSIO.OOO damages by Lawrence W. Burke,\n334 Indiana avenue, who charges\nnegligence in leaving unprotected a\ncellar door. The plaintiff says he was\nwalking along E street in front of the\ndefendant\u2019s place when he stepped Into\na hole and was thrown against an iron\ndoor leading to the cellar. He sustained\n1 serious injury, ha aaaerts. Attorney\nI. Q. H. Alward appears for the\nI plaintiff.\nt\nt \u2014\u2014a\u2014\u2014\u2014\ni\ni to be built. Taking into account the\ni new cruiser to be constructed at Mare\nIsland, only 6 of the If are being built\nat present. It has been found necessary\nto reduce the number of men at the\nWashington Navy Yard from the pea*\ni of around 4,000 to where It was before\ni the 15-crulser program was adopted.\nThe force la being retained Intact as\nlong as possible, naval officials as*\nserted, but a gradual reduction is going\nforward all the time. Within recent\nmonths the Washington Navy Yard\nhas discharged more than 500 men, but\ni officials said today that the alteration\ni In the turrent plans will not mean any\ngreat decrease.\nTHE EVENING STAR, WASHINGTON, I). C FRIDAY, OCTOBER 17, 1930.\nTHREE PERSONS DIE\nIN TRAIN COLLISION\nFour Others Injured as Big\nFour Locomotives Crash\nin Cleveland.\nBy the Aiwoclated Press.\nCLEVELAND, October 17\u2014Two mall\ntrains of the Big Four Railroad smashed\nhead-on within the city -early today,\nkilling three of their crews and in\npurlng four others.\nThrough some mix-up, a westbound\ntrain, departing for St. Louis, was on\nthe same track as another train coming\ninto the station from the divisional\nyards at Llnndale. They collided\nrounding a curve near the Fulton road\nbridge.\nThree Trainmen Killed.\nEngineer Henry Sprouse of the east\nbound train and Fireman Charles\nGraft, 65. and Conductor Jerry Dickson,\n50, of the westbound train were killed.\nEngineer Frank McCarthy of the west\nbound train and Fireman Clarence\nSheffield, 36, of the eastbound train,\nwere seriously scalded. Thomas Hena\nhan. 59, fireman on the eastbound train,\nand William F. Dee, flagman on the\nwestbound train, suffered minor In\njuries. All were from Cleveland.\nOfficials of the road declined to com\nment on the accident and witnesses\nwere unable to explain how it hap\npened. Each locomotive was pulling\ntwo wail coaches.\nSprouse and Graff were scalded to\ndeath in escaping steam, while Dlck\naon waa pinned between the cab and\ntender trying to jump. McCarthy and\nSheffield were too seriously injured to\ntell how the wreck occurred.\nNo Warning of Crash.\nHenahan, whose left arm was para\nlysed. said the east-bound train was\nrounding the curve at a slow rate of\nspeed. There was no warning of the\ncrash, he sqid,' and he had only a\nglimpse of the headlights of the on\ncoming locomotive before the impact.\nDee saved his life by jumping and\nwas knocked unconscious.\nThe locomotives telescoped, then sank\nback with their noses buried into each\nother. The heat of the ateam rush\ning from the broken boilers was so in\ntense that rescue workers were forced\nto work several hours with acetylene\ntorches to free the body of Dickson.\nNATION-WIDE PROBE\nOF BUS OPERATIONS\nOPENS NEXT MONTH\n(Continued From First Page.)\ngress by Representative Parkar of New\nYork, a member of the House Commit\ntee on Interstate and Foreign Com\nmerce. The bill is now in the status\nof \u2018\u2018unfinished business\u201d of the Senate.\nExtension of Tolley.\nIn its report on the bill the House\ncommittee said: \u201cThe principle of\nGovernment regulation of public utili\nties has been generally adopted in this\ncountry, both in Federal and State mat\nters. The enactment of legislation of\nthe character proposed will be merely\nthe extension of this principle to a\nutility which, although comparatively\nnew. is one which is developing with\ngreat rapidity in all parts of the United\nStates and bears a close relation to the\npublic interest.\u201d\nThe original recommendation of the\ncommission called for Federal control\nof all Interstate passenger traffic on the\nhighways to the extent that rates and\nfares be regulated, certificates showing\npublic convenience or necessity required\nand liability Insurance or indemnity\nbonds be demanded of the carriers.\nIt is recalled that although the origi\nnal Investigation by the commission\nembraced motor transportation of\nfreight as well as traffic, the commis\nsion deemed it advisable at the time\nto urge regulation only of commercial\npassenger traffic. The forthcoming In\nvestigation also will cover the broad\nfield of motor transportation.\nRegulation Favored.\nFederal regulation of Interstate bus\nand truck traffic apparently meets with\nthe approval of the transportation in\nterests Involved. The National Associa\ntion of Motor Bus Operators recently\nIndorsed the Parker bill, and the action\nof the but operators, in turn, has just\nbeen approved by the Executive Com\nmittee of the American Electric Rail\nway Association.\nHenry R. Trumbower. professor of\neconomics at the University of Wiscon\nsin and economist of the United States\nBureau of Roads, advised the recent\nInternational Road Congress here that\n\u201cco-operation between railroads and au\ntomobiles is one of the great require\nments of the age.\" Bus operation,\nwhether carried on by a railway com\npany or by an Independent operator,\nmust be conducted as a \"regulated\nmonopoly,\u201d the congress was told.\nCOUZENS OPERATED UPON\nDETROIT, October 17 OP).\u2014Senator\nJames Couse ns was operated on at\nHarper Hospital today for the removal\nof three bladder stones. The operation\nwaa performed by Dr. Max Ballln,\nassisted by Dr. W. K. Rexford, who re\nported the Senator\u2019s condition satis\nfactory.\nSenator Couzen* entered the hospital\nfor examination Tuesday and will re\nmain there for about three weeks.\nir\nTREATY COURIER\nCOMPLETES FLIGHT\nReaches New York After\nDash Which Cost Life\nof Lieut. Caldwell.\nBr the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, October 17.\u2014The offi\ncial text of Japan's ratification of the\nLondon naval treaty was here today,\nbrought across the continent by air,\ncourier on its way from Tokio to London, j\nLieut. Irving A. Woodring landeft at\nMltchel Field last night, ending the last\nstage of a dash from Victoria, British\nColumbia, with the document, which was\nbrought from Japan on a fast steamship.\nPierrt De L. Baol, assistant chief of\nthe Division of Western European Af\nfairs of the State Department, will board\nthe Leviathan with it tomorrow to de\nliver it to Ambassador Matsudaira in\nLondon.\nBeing Ruahed to London.\nThe ratification is being rushed to get\nIt to London before the opening of the\nsession of the League of Nations Dis\narmament Commission at Geneva.\nThe /ffort to hurry transmission of\nthe document by airplane cost the life\nof Lieut. William V. Caldwell, 27 years\nold. who was killed Wednesday when his\nescort plane crashed near Lookout, Wyo.,\nduring a blizzard. His body was found\nyesterday.\nLieut. Woodring left Victoria Wednes\nday in a fast Army pursuit plane, escort\ned by Lieut. Caldwell. The planes be\ncame separated in the blizzard. Wood\nring got through to Cheyenne.\nChanged Planes In Ohio.\nHe took off again yesterday morning,\nand after making brief stops for fuel at\nOmaha and Chicago, changed at Cleve\nland to a safer plane, piloted by Lieut.\nStanley Olmstead for the dash across\nthe Alleghanies.\nThe body of Caldwell, a member of\nthe Air Corps Reserve, was found by\nRay W. Mesklmen. a Boeing airmail\npilot. The plane was shattered. The\nmotor was found 50 feet from the\nwreckage, Indicating the plane had\nstruck the ground with terrific force.\nCaldwell's body was taken to Cheyenne.\nWINTER SWEEPING\nTOWARD CAPITAL\nEffect of Chilling Wave in West\nto Be Recorded Here\nby Tonight.\nB\u00bb the Associated Pres*.\nKANSAS CITY, October 17.\u2014Win\nter's first threat, which blanketed the\nCascades and Rockies deep with snow, i\ntoday had chilled the Great Plains, the\nMississippi Valley and was sending a\nbrisk norther across the Texas prairies.\nDamage to late crops, danger to stock\nand even loss of human life was re\nported from various sections which felt\nthe storm. A searching parly yes ter- j\nday discovered the body of Benedict\nUmhoefer, 42, Great Falls, Mont., who\nhad perished in a snowstorm,\nv Blizzards swept along the Judith\nValley of Montana early today, where\na minimum temperature of 7 above zero\nwas reported. Temperatures continued\nto fall in other parts of the State as\nthe snowstorm of yesterday abated.\nA heavy snowstorm swept the We\nnatchee Valley in Washington, said by\nresidents to be the earliest snowfall\nsince 1916. Low clouds over the Cas\ncades threatened a renewal of ihe storm\nthere.\nSnow was reported, too, throughout\nthe Rocky Mountain region, the Da\nkotas and Minnesota.\nRapidly failing temperatures in lowa.\nNebraska and Missouri brought threat*\nof early frosts. Freezing temperature\nstruck Western Kansas late yesterday.\nIn Oklahoma the temperature had\ntumbled from 7$ degrees at 8 a.m., yes\nterday. to 44 at midnight, with the drop\ncontinuing. A cold northerly wind was\nsweeping across Texas chilling the j\nState, which enjoyed temperatures well\nover 80 yesterday.\nThe unseasonably warm weather here\nfor the past week will be broken to\nnight, when the effects of the cold wave j\nwhich passed over the Rocky Mountains\nseveral days ago wiH be felt in the Na-1\ntional Capital, the forecaster at the\nWeather Bureau predicted today. A i\ntemperature of about 48 degrees will be\nreached some time tonight, he said, with i\npossible showers.\nWhile stating it will be colder here,\nthe forecaster emphasized that there is\nno \u201ccold wave\u201d in immediate prospect\nfor the District of Columbia, but stated i\nit will seem much colder due to the un- i\nseasonably warm weather, which is pass- j\nlng.\n70 ALLEGED SPYS HELD\nIN RUMANIA ROUND-UP\nUnofficial Report Says Many Rus\nsians Believed Implicated\nin Arrests.\nBy the Associated Press.\nBUCHAREST. Rumania. October 17.\n\u2014Seventy arrests have been made in a\nround-up of alleged espionage agents, j\nin whlcn, an unofficial report today\nsaid, many foreigners, including Rus\nsians, are believed implicated.\nThe report said that the affair would\nprobably prove to be the most sensa\ntional exposure of intrigue in favor of\nRussia ever made in the country.\nIts discovery apparently was made\nby the authorities only today and de\ntails have not been disclosed, although\nit was admitted that the arrests had\nbeen effected and that others were to\nfollow.\nMcBRIDE TO BE FREED\nOhio Officials Will Not Fay Costs\nof Extradition.\nEmmet Mc\u00dfride, 50-year-old brother\nof Dr. F. Scott Mc\u00dfride, superintendent\nof the Anti-Saloon League, held 4n cus\ntody here since Tuesday afternoon\nawaiting word from the Steubenville,\nOhio, authorities, where he was reported\nwanted on bad-check charges, will be i\nreleased this afternoon.\nRosa H. Cunningham, chief of police\nof Steubenville, notified the local police\nthat the State would not defray the ex\npenses of extradition proceedings. In\nspector William S. Shelby, chief of de\ntectives, conferred with Dr. Mc\u00dfride in\nan effort to assist the brother.\nLAW BOARD ADJOURNS\nReport on Bnforcement Delayed\nUntil After Election.\nThe Law Enforcement Commission,\nengaged in the preparation of a report\non prohibition, recessed today until after\nthe November 4 elections.\nChairman Wlckersham clamped tight\nthe lid of secrecy as the commission\nbroke up. He indicated, however, that\nthere had been no division within the\ncommission upon prohibition.\nThe members were notified by the\nchairman to resume their work here the\nday after elections.\nIBRAZILIAN REBELS\nCAPTURE CAPITAL\nAracaju Capitulates With\nLittle Struggle to Ta<\nvora\u2019s Forces.\n(Continued From First Page\ngovernment to resign and at the same\nI time added a warning that if the gov\nernment should insist upon opposing\ni the revolution, the Insurgents would\nI not be responsible for the shedding of h\nj blood.\nGen. Costa's message follows:\n\"Brazilians: Five thousand gauchos\n(cowboys), constituting the advance\nguard of the liberation army, have\nalready occupied Itare, Capella, Ribelra\nand various other secondary places.\n\"In order to prevent further shed\nding of blood, we invited the minister\nof war to send planes to examine the\nrailroad from itarare to Marcellno\nRamos, and we told them that their\nplanes may land in our field at Pirahy,\nPonta Gorssa, and Castro, where we\nshall provide them with all the ele\nments that they may need. We gave\nthem our word of honor to allow them\nto come and go freely and we are\nready to give them all the necessary\nhelp. In this manner they may realize\nthe immenseness of our resources and\nthe vast possibilities lying ahead of us\nIn our march northward, to effect a\njunction with the forces which hold\nthe north.\nUltimatum Is Delivered.\n\"By the defeat already inflicted in\nthe battles of Joinvllle, Quiatigua. Af\nfonro Camargo and Slngues It may be\nseen that It is useless for them to sac\nrifice more lives.\n\"In all these encounters the federal\nforces, demoralized, without the will to\nfight, surrendered en masse or fled at\nthe outset of the battle with the brave\ndefenders of the national cause. The\nindescribable enthusiasm with which we\nhave been received everywhere proves\nthe aacredness and the popularity of\nour cause.\n\u2018\u2018Within a few days our troops will\npass through Sao Paulo territory, where\nwe are expecting a large number of ad\nherents. With all this we feel powerful\nand we have absolute confidence in a\ncomplete victory, for which reason we\nshall accept no conditions.\n\"Convinced of its own impotence, the\nfederal government should resign, de*\nliverlng themselves to our generosity\nand to the loftiness of our ideals\u2014ldeals\nfor which we are fighting and which\nare the constitution of a Brazil great\nand free from professional politicians.\nVictory is Expected.\n\u201cShould the federal government insist\nin their vain effort to bppose the reali\nzation of the revolutionary ideals. We\nwant to tell them that after the victory,\nwhich soon will come as the reward of\nour efforts, we will not be responsible\nfor the fate of those who are to be\nblamed for the useless shedding of\nblood.\n\"Signed Gen. Miguel Costa.\u201d\nLess than two weeks ago. Capt. Ta\nvora. leading an army of 8.000 and as\ni slated by volunteers from the State of\nParahyba, raided Pernambuco and,\nafter considerable fighting, seined the\ncity and established a revolutionary\n1 government there. Consolidating his\nforces, and reinforced by thousands of\nvolunteers from Pernambuco, he ln-\nI adrd the State of Alagoas, taking\nMaceio, capital of the state.\nHe stayed there only a few days be\nfore beginning his march Into Sergipe.\nThe communique stated that a heavy\nconcentration of troops was In progress\nalong the Parana-Bao Paulo frontier, a\nregion where the federal and insurgent\narmies have been gathering for the\nlast few dsys for whst has loomed up\nas a major engagement. Observers, in\nfact, today expressed the opinion that\nthe present gathering of troops along\nthis line was the greatest concentration\never seen In South America.\nReport Regiment Surrender.\nWhile not stating the number of sol\ndiers involved, the Insurgents made the\nclaim that 80 companies of federals at\nCatharlna had gone over to the revolu\ntion. These men were said to be under\nthe command of Capt. Mario Carvalho.\nTwo machine guns and much more ma\nterial were taken over.\nThe federal regiment reported to have\nsurrendered was described as the 11th\nInfantrv, stationed In the state of\nMinas Oeraes. These troops had been\nsurrounded by the insurgents, and their\nsurrender was said to be without condi\ntion. _\nIn reporting this victory, the official\nrebel communique atated that thus far\nthe rebela had not met with a reverse\nin Minas Geraes.\nINSURGENTS VICTORIOUS.\nImportant Interior City Taken \u2014Feder-\nate Begin Advance.\nMONTEVIDEO. Uruguay. October 17\n(7P>. \u2014An official revolutionary com\nminique today aaid that insurgent Bra\nzilian forces had captured the important\ninterior city of Sao Joao D'El-Rey, the\n110th Federal Infantry stationed there\nj surrendering unconditionally,\nj Bao Joao 'DEI-Ray Is located on one\nof the two rail routes from Rio Janeiro\nto Bello Horizonte, capital of the state,\nand is a city of 80.000 population. The\nInfantry regiment had been besieged by\nthe insurgent* since beginning of the\nrevolution.\nBrazilian federal reports from Rio de\nJaneiro claimed that the federal armies\nwere advancing \"on all fronts\u201d in Minas i\nGeraes. and that In many localities the\ntroops were encountering no resistance.\nRebel troops were said in Rio de Janeiro\ndispatches to have abandoned Santa\nRita do Jacutlnga and retreated to Im\nbutiero.\nThe dispatches said that many pris\noners had been taken by the federals\nin the Juiz de Fora sector, which is lo\ncated In the southeastern part of the\nstate, about 50 miles southeast of Sao\nJoao D'El-Ray, now occupied by rebels.\nThe Rio de Janeiro aources also said\nthat there had been another attack on\nItarare.important rail head, on the bor\nder of Parana, in Sao Paulo, and that\n300 prisoners had been taken. Two\nhundred of these arrived at Sao Paulo\nby special train.\nINDIAN LEADER ARRESTED\nBOMBAY. India. October 17 (TP).\nOsman sobhani, who was elected presi\ndent of the All-India National Congress\nWgr Council last Wednesday, was ar\nrested today.\nMrs. Annie Beaant, theosophical\nleader, arriving here today, said in an\ninterview: \"I am and have always been\nagainst the campaign of civil disobedi-\nI enoe and have not been prepared to fol\nj low It myself.\"\nShe paid tribute to Wedgwood Benn,\ni secretary of state of India, who, ahe\ndeclared, was sincerely working for In\ndia.\nOther arrests today included Secre\ntary Kersondas of the Boycott Commit\ntee, Meherally. dictator of the Youth\nLeague; Parekh, editor of the proscribed\nCongress Bulletin, and Bhuta, secretary\nto the War Council.\nEMBEZZLEMENT CHARGED\nOKLAHOMA CITY, October 17 (TP).\n\u2014A complaint charging embezzlement\nof 530,000 by E. L. Fitzgerald. Coving\nton and Billings banker, was filed here\nyesterday by Roy St. Lewis, United\nStates district attorney.\nThe Billings National Bank, in which\nFitsgerald was principal stockholder,\nand the American State Bank of\nCovington, in which he waa an active\nofficer, had been closed.\nLewis alleged Flttgarald appropriated\nmoney, funds and credit of the\nBillings Bank by placing in the bank a\nworthless issue of $30,000 in Covington\ncity bonds.\nk\nINVITE HOOVER TO AD SESSIONS\nhSgBQ/m\nMembers of the Executive Committee of the National Advertisers\u2019 Associa\ntion called at the White House yesterday to invite President Hoover to address\ntheir convention in Washington November 16. In the group, left to right: Allyn\nB. Mclntire, Boston. Mast.; Bennett Chappie, Middletown, Ohio; Lee Bristol,\nNew York City; A. E. Hasse, New York City, and O. N. Solbert, Rochester, N. V.\n\u2014Wide World Photo.\nLENIENCY TO END\nFOR COMMUNISTS\n16 Now Under Arrest for\nSeries of Riots \u2014Walker\nCalled \u201cGrafter and Crook.\u201d\nNEW YORK, October 17 UP).\u2014An\nend to official leniency toward Com\nmunist* demonstrations was predicted\ntoday as the party\u2019s candidate for lieu\ntenant governor and several Red sym\npathisers awaited arraignment on\ncharges growing out of a series of riots\nyesterday.\nMayor Walker, whom one Communist\ncalled a \u201cdirty grafter\u201d in a meeting of\nthe Board of Estimate just before night\nsticks came into play, declared today the\nrioters got what they deserved from the\npolice.\nCites Disorderly Behavior.\n\u2018\u2018Every opportunity for orderly Tiro\ntest was given a Communist delegation\nadmitted to a budget meeting of the\nBoard of Estimate,\u201d he said, \"but when\ntheir spokesman insisted on discussing\nunemployment out of its proper place\nin the business calendar. I asked if they\npreferred to be orderly or disorderly,\nThey preferred to be disorderly.\u201d\nThe administration, the mayor said, 1\nhas done everything it can to relieve j\nunemployment, but rioting will accom\nplish nothing constructive.\nThreatened to Thrash Speaker.\nPersonal abuse from one Communist\nat the meeting did not bother him, the i\nmayor said, until it reached a point\n\u201cwhere the people of the city had the j\nright to expect me to be a man or resign\nfrom the position I hold.\"\nHe was referring to his threat to I\nretaliate with his own hands for the\ninsults flung at him by the Communist\nspeaker.\nPOLICE SEIZE It RIOTERS.\nReds Invade City Hall-\u2014Dozens Hurt as\nPolice Disperse Crowds.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. October 17.\u2014Six\nteen persons were under arrest today as\nthe result of a series of Communist\nriots which came to s climax when a\nI party of Reds Invaded City Hall and\none of them called Mayor Walker \"a\ngrafting Tammany politician and a\nctook.\u201d\nAn attempt by a group of Communists\nto present an unemployment petition at\na meeting of the Board of Estimate, over i\nv'hich the mayor was presiding, pre\ncipitated the disturbance In the City\nHall.\nAnother clash occurred in City Hall j\nPark and at Broadway and Barclay\nstreet, in which two plate glass windows\nIn the Woolworth Building v.erc\nsmashed.\nDozens Injured.\nA young woman suffered minor in\njuries when she was trampled by a\npoliceman's horse, and dozens suffered\nbruises and slight cuts as police used\nnightsticks and blackjacks to disperse 1\nthe yelling, lighting mob.\nAmong those arrested was Louis J.\nEngdahl, secretary of the International\nLabor Defense and Communist candi\ndate for lieutenant governor, who at- I\ntempted to make speeches outside after I\nhe had been ejected from the Board of j\nEstimate meeting.\nThe lighting In the City Hall was pre- j\ncipltated when Sam Nessin. who as\nsumed charge of the petitioners after\nEngdahl's ejection, shouted to Mayor\nWalker.-\nCalled \"Grafter and Crook.\u201d\n\"You are a lot of grafting Tammany\npoliticians. I would rather be a mem\nber of my working class than one of\nyour grafting officials. You are a graft\ning Tammany politician and a crook.\"\nThe mayor rose from his seat and\nreplied, \"That little remark prompts\nme to come dow-n and thrash the life\nout of you.\u201d\nMembers of the audience and police\nsurrounded Nessin and his companions\nand rushed them out of the room and\ndown the stairs, pummeling them the\nmeanwhile. Police took a hand, and\nafter much disorder in which Nessin\nwas severely beaten, he and two others\nw-ere arrested. Nessin was charged with\ninciting a riot, and Robert Leless and\nMilton Stone were held for assault.\nMaude White, a negro woman In the\ndelegation, escaped.\nThe second riot broke out when Com\u00ab\nmunists and sympathizers rallied\naround Engdahl in front of the Wool\nworth Building, where he attempted to\nspeak. Mounted police rode their horses\ninto the crowd several times to break\nit up.\nJabs Police Horse With Pin.\nA woman jabbed a pin into the flank\nof one of the police horses And when\nthe animal plunged, the crowd pressed\nagainst the window of a drug store,\nshattering It. A moment later another\nwindow was smashed In.\nOther disturbances occurred at Sixth\navenue and Fort*-th street, where six\npersons were arrested, and at Sixth\navehue and Thirty-ninth street, where\npolice took four more prisoners, includ\ning a woman.\nA night court hearing for those ar\nrested in the City Hall and vicinity was\nthe occasion for another demonstration.\nEngdahl and two woman prisoners\nspurned an offer of leniency from\nMagistrate Ootlleb and delivered a\ntirade, after which Engdahl wa# ordered\ntaken back to the prisoners\u2019 pen.\nHe and the two men were held in\n1500 bail each for appearance in Tombs\nCourt today. Leless and Stone wei.\nparoled in custody of their attorneys\nfor examination November 20.\nNorman W. Mowbray, one of the most\nexpert of the Scottish mountain climb\ners, fell 500 feet to his death in Ar\ngyllshire.\n\nHOOVER CONFERS\nWITH B. M. BARUCH\nBusiness Situation Discussed\nin Series of White House\nTalks With Leaders.\nPresident Hoover conferred for several\nhours last night upon the general bus-\nI mess situation with Bernard M. Baruch,\nNew York financier and nationally\ni prominent Democrat. Mr. Barurh was\na guest at dinner at the White House.\nand afterwards he and the President\ni talked in the latter\u2019s study on the sec\nond floor until the time arrived for Mr.\nBaruch to hurry to the station to catch\nthe midnight train back to New York.\nLast night\u2019s conference is looked upon\nas of real Importance, not only because\nI of Mr. Baruch's position in the financial\nworld, but because it was one of a\nseries of such conferences Mr. Hoover\nwill hold from time to time with finan\ncial and business leaders.\nKeeps President Posted.\nAccording to the President himself\nthese conferences are for the purpose\nof keeping him posted as to business\nconditions and possible trends. Also,\nthe President Is known to have advices\nto the effect that a business revival Is on\nthe horizon and to substantiate this he\nis seeking the opinions of those men\nwhom he believes are in positions to\nadvise him correctly.\nAdditional importance is attached to\nlast night\u2019s conference as well as to the\ni one preceding it because of the specu\nlation to the effect that Pr;sident\nI Hoover is eager to do what is possible\nto steady the stock market, particularly\nj under the repeated attacks of short\ni sellers.\nIt is known that the President has\nI been advised by administration asso\ni elates that the Federal Government is\nwithout power to take any direct action\nto curb bearish assaults and therefore\nit is understood that in his determina\ntion to do something helpful Mr. Hoover\nis calling men of finance and business,\nnot only to get their views but their\ncc-operation.\nOther Leaders Seen.\nMr. Hoover's conference with Mr.\nBaruch followed close upon the heels of\ncth*r conferences held last Sundav\nnight at the White House with Richard\nI Whitney, president of the New York\nI Stock Exchange, and Allen Lindley.\nchairman of the Business Conduct\nCommittee o\u2018s the New York exchange.\nI Other prominent figures who have con\nfarred with President Hoover since he\ninitiated these conferences about three\ni weeks ago are Alfred P. Sloan, presi\ndent of the General Motors Corporation,\nI \u00bbnd Charles Hayden. Boston and New\nYork banker and broker,\ni The President also has conferred re\ncently with Eugene Myer. jr.. the new\ni governor of the Federal Reserve Board\nMr. Myer, by the way. Is one of the\nPresident\u2019s associates who holds that\nthe Government can do nothing offi\ncially to steady the stock market if he\nso desires.\nOth\u00bbr than to say that the general\nbusiness situation was discussed during\nthe President\u2019s conference with Mr.\nBaruch last night, the White House to\ndsy would make no further comment.\nIt did state, however, that the Presi\ndsnt expects to hold more of these con\nferences from time to time. Mr. Baruch\nwas advisory commissioner of the\nCouncil of National Defense during the\nj World War and chairman of the Com\ni mittee on Raw Materials for the War\ni Industry Board and otherwise promi\nnently ldsntlfled with the Wilson ad\nministration throughout the war.\nBaruch Declines Comment.\nNEW YORK. October 17 (Ah.\u2014Ber\nnard Baruch, New York capitalist, de-\nI dined to comment today on his confer\nence with President Hoover last night,\nmerely stating that he discussed the\n\u201cgeneral economic situation.\u201d\nBOY AIR RECORD SEEKER\nHOPS OFF FOR ST. LOUIS\nBuck Leaves Wichita After Spend\ning Three Days There to Es\ncape Foga.\nBy the Associated Press.\nWICHITA. Kans., October 17. Rob\nert Buck, 16-year-old Elizabeth, N. J.,\nflyer, attempting to better the junior\nWest-East transcontinental flight rec\nord. took off at 7:18 a.m. (Central\nstandard time), today for St. Louis.\nDue to unfavorable weather, the\nyouthful aviator\u2019s flight from Los An\ngeles to New York has been interrupted\nfrequently. He tarried three nights in\nWichita hoping to escape strong head\nwinds and fogs.\nHe was forced to remain In Amarillo,\nTex., two days, finally breaking away In\nthe face of a storm. His total elapsed\nflying time to Wichita was 12 hours\nand 9 minut?s\nEXPELLED FOR SMOKING,\nGIRL, 14, ENDS HER LIFE\nMother Says Pupil Felt She Had\nBeen Disgraced and Brooded\nOver Dismissal.\nBy the Associated Pres*.\nDETROIT, October 17\u2014A 14-year\nold who felt she had been disgraced be\ncause she was expelled from school after\naccusation of smoking cigarettes, com\nmitted suicide yesterday by drowning\nin the Detroit River.\nHer moth?r said the girl, Dorothy\nBerger, had denied the accusation and\nhad brooded over her dismissal. A week\nago she disappeared from home. Last\nnight her mother and sister identified\nher body )n the county morgue.\nA\nFASCISTS DECURE\nPUCE PACT VOID\nHours of Bedlam Mark Ger\nman Reichstag Session\nAfter Street Riots.\n(Continued From First Page.)\nto end the demonstration the Hitlerites,\nat a signal from a floor leader, shouted\nthree times, \u201cGermany, awake!\u201d\nOffer Radical Motion.\nAfter Strasser's address the Fascists\nintroduced a motion in the Reichstag\ndemanding \"expropriation without in\ndemnification'\u2019 for the benefit of the\nGerman peoples of the entire capital\nof bank and Bourse magnates, of East\nEuropean Jews and others of foreign\nrace who had immigrated to Germany\nsince August 1, 1914.\nTo make the motion more sweeping,\nit was extended to the families of rela\ntives of these and to moneys Invested\nand increased since that date through\nwar. revolution, inflation, deflation and\nprofiteering.\u201d\nThe motion also demanded that the\ngovernment take over immediately all\nbig banks, including the Reichsbank.\nThe Communist Wilhelm Pleck. used\nthe forum chiefly for a tirade against\nmetal manufacturers, hut he also de\nlivered a bitter attack against the gov\nernment, while his colleagues cried\n\u2022Red front!\u201d. He spoke before an al\nmost empty house.\nCentrist AMs Government.\nThe Centrist, Joseph Joos, declared\nthat his party supported the govern\nment's declaration. He said, \u201cBy the\nvery fact of remaining in office, our\ngovernment has strengthened the con\nfidence of foreign countries in Ger\nmany.\u201d\nTher? mere no conciliatory utterances\nvoiced in the Reichstag todays A high\nlight of the opposite attitude came\nwhen the Fascist spokesman. Strassar,\nturning to the Social Democratic\nbenches, shouted, \u201cIf the Prussian Diet\nis \u2019not dissolved now, we do not mind.\nWe can wait because the future is with\nus. The time is not distant when we\nwill use law for protection of the re\npublic against you.\n\u201cWe are for the constitution and We\nshall maintain ourselves in power on\nthe strength of it* Just wait until the\nday for squaring accounts with you\ncomes.\u201d\nHostile elements previously had\nheckled Finance Minister Dietrich and\nall but made ft impossible for him to\nexplain the government's fiscal needs.\nOutbreak on Streets.\nToday\u2019s Reichstag disturbances had\nfollowed a more serious outbreak in\nthe streets of the Wedding industrial\ndistrict in the night, which had spread\nover a considerable area.\nDuring these disorders, Die police\nsaid, half a dozen shots were fired by\nsnipers from windows and roofs, and\nthe authorities had to take cover. This\nsection of the city was under heavy\nguard today, while armed officers\nsearched of firearms every person at\ntempting to enter the area. No house\ni to-house search wss undertaken, but\nthere was no let-up of vigilance.\nThe harass the police the dispersed\nrioters, before daylight, burst Inflated\npaper bags. Imitating gun shots.\nInjured by Rocks.\nSeemingly no policeman was wound\ned by bullets, but several were seri\nously injured by rock throwers. The\nCommunists, to whom the authorities\nattached the blame for the disorders,\ncharged that some of their people had\nbeen ehot.\nThey said their members had fired\nshots into the air during the shooting\nfrom the other side, but had taken\ncare not to hit anybody.\nThe streets of the zone today were\nlitter: d with crockery, saucepans, flower\npots and kindred household objects\nwhich had been thrown frdm the upper\nwindows on the riot squads.\nA storm arose almost at the outset\nof the debate, shortly after the Com\nmunist. Theodor Neubau:r, arose to dis\ncuss the government measure authoris\ning an international loan of $125,000,-\n000 covering Germany's deficit.\nThreats Are Defied.\nPresident Loebe trhd vigorously to\nrestore order, ringing his bell and, call\ning the hecklers by name, warning\nthem that they would be suspended.\n\"Throw them out;\u2019\u2019 the Socialists\ncall:d at the Right benches.\n\u201cJust try to throw any of us out,\u201d the\nFascists shouted back.\nHerr Dietrich pleaded with the Fas\ncists, or National Socialists, not to in\ncrease the feeling of panic in the coun\ntry by constantly challenging each esti\nmate presented in connection with the\nfinancial program.\nIn a raised voice, he cried: \u201cYou sim\nply cannot smash everything and rob\nour people of the last ounce of courage\nby saying \u2018events will show conditions\nworse than you anticipated.\u2019\nDefends Finance Flan.\n\u201cI doubt whether by painting every\nthing blackest you are rendering a serv\nice to the German people. You have\nnever yet made a constructive proposal\nhow to get out of our debt. Our plan\nwipes out tne floating debt, in three\nyears.\u201d\nThe Fascist? introduced a new note\ninto their pai liamentary tactics when\nFormer Chancellor Mueller, one of the\nsigners of the treaty of Versailles,\nmounted the rostrum on behalf of the\nSocial Democrats. The Fascists ex\nclaimed in a chorus, \"Mueller of Ver\nsailles. Mueller of Versailles!\u201d and\nwalked out of the hall.\nThe example of the National Socialists\nwas followed by the Nationalists, headed\nby Dr. Hugenberg. and by the Farmer's\nFederation so that virtually all benches\nto the right were ostentatiously empty.\nLater, however, six or seven Fascists re\nturned to their seats and joined the\nCommunists in heckling the former\nchancellor, who proceeded imperturb\nably to defend his course at Versailles.\nParty Reserves Decisions.\nHerr Mueller declared that if times\nwere not so serious the Socialists would\noppose the government and especially\nthe ministers, Schiele and Treviranus,\nbut in view of the Fascist and Nation\nalist attitude his party would decide for\nitself when to vote no confidence.\nTo a Fascist deputy named Koch from\nEast Prussia came the distinction of\nbeing the first member of the present\nParliament ordered out of the plenary\nhall by President Loebe. When he in\nsisted upon interrupting the speaker,\nLoebe first threatened and then ordered\nhim out.\nKoch tried at flrat to remain, de\nfiant, but the better counsel of hLs\nfriends prevailed and he departed\npeacefully.\nWorkless on Increase.\nHerr Dietrich explained the Qerman\nfloating debt now is 1,213.000.000.000\nmarks (about $304,250,000). Increas\ning unemployment, he said, has neces\nsitated vastly higher unemployment\ndoles than had been originally assumed.\nThe budget, he said, has therefore\nbeen revised on the assumption of\n1,600.000 unemployed receiving doles\nwould by February have increased to\n2.600,000. Nevertheless, he pointed out,\nthe new budget, provided for 1,000,000,-\n000 marks less expenditure than dur\ning the past year.\nIn response to a challenge from the\nfloor Herr Dietrich stated emphatical\nly that in negotiating the credit of\n$125,000,000 to cover the Reich deficit\nthe government offered no German\nmonopoly as a base, nor had it re\nnounced possibility of invoking a mora\ntorium under provisions of the Young\nplan.\nMiss England IL the speedboat ir\nwhich Sir Henry Segrave lost his Ufa\nis being reconditioned at point is\nDerby.","height":"25407","width":"19791"}}
